data.content:
Yes! For simple constant values, use `[DataRow]` directly — no need for `DynamicData` or `object[]`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

If you need **non-constant data** (objects, computed values), you can add type safety with tuples:

```csharp
public static IEnumerable<object[]> TestData =>
    new (string Input, bool Expected)[]
    {
        ("valid@email.com", true),
        ("invalid", false),
        ("", false),
    }.Select(t => new object[] { t.Input, t.Expected });
```

**TL;DR:** `[DataRow]` is simpler and type-checked at compile time. Reserve `DynamicData` for when test data is computed or contains non-constant types.
